subSubSection.paragraph:
Skeletal architecture: The cortex has a thickness of 
225–350 µm
(
Fig. 2B
) and consists mainly of aspidasters which are arranged in several layers with the flat side parallel to the surface. Cladomes of dichotriaenes (
Fig. 2C
) support the cortex from the choanosome with the rhabdome usually directed into the choanosome (
Fig. 3A
). Directly above the aspidasters on the surface are irregularly distributed microstrongyles (
Fig. 2F
). Dichotriaenes are rare in spicule preparations but were observed densely arranged below the cortex with the clads embedded into the cortex (
Fig. 3A
). The choanosome consists of oxeas, occasionally styles and asters without any obvious order.
